## wget (used to send an HTTP POST/GET/.. request with a JSON body to an API endpoint.
>> below example is being used to create (POST) an object on the server.

wget \
  --method POST \
  --timeout=0 \
  --header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  --body-data '{
    "name": "Apple MacBook Pro 1999",
    "data": {
        "year": 2019,
        "price": 1849.99,
        "CPU model": "Intel Core i9",
        "Hard disk size": "1 TB"
    }
}' \
   'https://api.restful-api.dev/objects'

(can also pass json file in body-data)
wget --method POST \
  --timeout=30 \
  --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --body-data @"C:\testdata\payload.json" \
  https://api.restful-api.dev/objects

## Performance testing using json-server
>>json-server lets you simulate a backend API quickly for development, testing, or automation without writing server code.
>>npm i -g json-server (installing json server)
>> create server.json in project d
>>json-server server.json (run the server)
>>we can add data to server.json using postman or jMeter by adding httpRequest

### performance testing  using jMeter
>> install JMeter Apache
>> command to run jmeter file using bash command
>>jmeter -n -l result.jtl -o report -e -t JMeterRequests.jmx
>>with json data
>>jmeter -n -l result.jtl -o report -e -t jMeterHttpReqDay2.jmx -JdataFile=jMeterReqCSV.csv -Jthreads=$lines


